Near 70-year-old Putin feels that if he wants to leave a deep mark in Russian history, it's either now or never.
But he has a distorted view of Russia's role in the world.
He seems to think that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
This system is diametrically opposed to democratic societies, and this vision has distorted the "soul" of Russia's people, who are emotionally and sentimentally inclined.
In my childhood, I had many contacts with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share their last loaf of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched my so-called political charity work.
In my youth, I established a foundation in my native Hungary, and subsequently actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
In my youth, I also established a foundation in Russia, and subsequently, in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, and even before it became an independent nation, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation, which I closed in 1989, shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre.
I have been following Putin's rise closely, despite not knowing him personally, and I have a thorough understanding of his ruthless character.
He would reduce Chechnya's capital city of Grozny to rubble, and now he is threatening to do the same to Ukraine's capital city of Kyiv.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he appears to have undergone a change of late.
He seems to have lost touch with reality, having formed a fixed notion.
Without a doubt, he has misjudged the Ukraine situation.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out they are no different from the Ukrainian-speaking civilians.
In the face of seemingly one-sided odds, Ukrainian civilians have displayed an incredible, courageous resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are, in fact, one people, while Ukrainians have fallen prey to the manipulation of neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kyiv is the site of the original Russian Orthodox Church, his argument in the first part is not entirely without historical basis.
But it was Putin who was misled in the second part of his argument.
He should have been more aware of the facts.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the 2014 Euromaidan protests in Independence Square.
The 2014 events left him extremely angry.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian troops performed poorly.
The Ministry's entrenched corruption also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin did not blame himself, and instead seemed to have lost his grip on reality.
He has made up his mind to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to be unbridled.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle, disregarding all rules of engagement, particularly bombing civilian populations indiscriminately.
Numerous hospitals were attacked, and the power grid that supplies the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In the besieged Mariupol, up to 400,000 people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia may likely lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are both shipping defensive weapons to Ukraine, while attempting to purchase Russian-made MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These developments may alter the entire situation.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already achieved a miracle in bolstering European resolve and unity.
It seems that Xi Jinping has already realized Putin has gone off the rails.
On March 8, following China's Foreign Minister Wang Yi's assertion that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock", Xi Jinping called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid triggering a humanitarian crisis, he wishes to exercise maximum restraint in the war.
Whether Putin will yield to Xi's wishes remains completely uncertain.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi Jinping will be ousted before they destroy our civilization.
